fields.text:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Much has been said about Witches. It would be foolish to think this was entirely by their design. It would also be rather foolish to assume this has been entirely to their benefit. However, the monumental position that Witches have in human culture is largely by their design, and it has largely been to their benefit. The stories you may have heard about witches throughout history, in that clever way that old stories often find a way of being, are entirely true. They are also, in that mundane, disappointing way that reality always imposes on things, entirely works of fiction.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;The secret that every good Witch knows is this: Fiction and Reality are not mutually exclusive.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;The fact remains that a Witch is in every way exactly what you would expect her to be, while at any moment capable of things you would never expect her to do.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lilith Araneus Midnight looked down at the spell she had constructed and took a deep breath. She grinned softly to herself. She rarely smiled, more rarely still in public, but she had the sort of smile that was clearly not a good sign. She had a smile that was most definitely at someone else&amp;rsquo;s expense.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Unlike Lilith&amp;rsquo;s smile, she was not born with her name. Her original name has been lost to history, or at least to the very definite impression that she will make suffer anyone who might try to sneak a glance at her passport.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Much like the Witch herself, names are fluid things. Lilith had decided at a young age that her name could be whatever she wanted it to be, and so she chose something that would suit the image she wanted to present for herself - Lilith Greene. A few years later, when she was at a slightly less young age, she decided she wasn&amp;rsquo;t going to be a botanist and changed her name again. She eventually discovered her true passion - being generally terrifying - and so her image and name settled on their ultimate forms.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is here that any description might feel the need to resort to vapid, flowery language about Lilith&amp;rsquo;s appearance. Though she did, as it happens, have on her person the various female body parts usually described with words like &amp;ldquo;lithe&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;supple,&amp;rdquo; it would be an insult to her to limit a description to that which she has in common with most other humans. She could, indeed, use her femininity to her advantage when she needed. However, when someone appears in a big, dark cloak, silhouetted against some lightning as they cackle maniacally into the night, onlookers don&amp;rsquo;t usually concern themselves with how gracefully that person&amp;rsquo;s hips will sway. Beauty is, of course, only skin deep. Power was always more important to her, and power coursed through her blood.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Her spell that night had been well made - perhaps her best yet. The quality of work wasn&amp;rsquo;t a surprise, of course. She had been practicing for quite a long time. Oneiromancy was a very difficult and subtle art. The trick was finding the right scale.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She had started, many years ago, trying to manipulate world events as a whole. This proved fruitless, as working at that sort of scale would require much more power than even Lilith had. The trick, she realized, was thinking small. Act locally, think locally-er. It is easy to manipulate individuals, to gently guide them down a path that you chose for them. The flow of events is like a river. You can&amp;rsquo;t just change what direction the river flows, but if you add a few strategically placed trees upstream, the flow will be ever-so-subtly affected. Over time the banks will begin to change. It would take time, but Lilith had plenty of that.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There was a tap on the window. A large black raven peered inside, his massive eye reflecting the crescent moon. It was Bodach, Lilith&amp;rsquo;s familiar. At least, he was familiar to her. She called him her familiar in the same way that she called her sisters Agnes and Clarinda her &amp;ldquo;colleagues.&amp;rdquo; Bodach didn&amp;rsquo;t speak to her - at least not in the way old fairy tales might suggest. He didn&amp;rsquo;t transform or give her some mystical second sight. He wasn&amp;rsquo;t magical at all. Bodey was simply Lilith&amp;rsquo;s pet. Familiar just sounds so much more Witchy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lilith had a deep fondness for ravens, as might be expected looking at her wardrobe. She appreciated the way their dark, mysterious quality supported her own. Bodach - this particular one, anyway - was the latest in a long line of birds all named Bodach lucky enough to win her favor. They were always ravens, they were always huge, and they were always male.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She blew out a number of candles that were placed in a ceremonially important arrangement on the floor, and then strode to the window.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Hello, Bodey,&amp;rdquo; she said sweetly as she opened the window. If anyone knew she spoke to animals in such a gentle way she would quickly make sure they didn&amp;rsquo;t know for long. &amp;ldquo;What have you brought me this evening?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It would have been nice if she could convince her familiars to bring her useful things. At the end of the day, however, they were always just ravens. Ravens have a habit of picking up random bits of falderal that they find interesting. Usually the things they find interesting are things that another person had thrown away. Often those things were in varying levels of decomposition. More than once it was a cigarette butt. Lilith added their less toxic offerings to a little altar, which over the years had become a massive piece of terrifyingly unwieldy folk art. Lilith liked to think it was full of the energy of those who hand handled the components through the years. An onlooker might assume it was full of disease.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bodey tilted his head, a stretch of red ribbon dangling from his beak.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, you silly little boy,&amp;rdquo; Lilith continued, taking the ribbon. &amp;ldquo;You know your mistress so well.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She scratched his head, and he closed his eyes and nuzzled into her fingers affectionately. She tied the ribbon loosely around one of her necklaces, and it hung between her collarbones like an open wound. Perfect.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lilith&amp;rsquo;s wardrobe was almost entirely black. It was not quite entirely black simply because a few bright red accents always go a very long way in the symbolism department. Likewise, the grey streak in her hair seemed to serve simply as a sinister taunt, inviting any poor unfortunate passerby to question her age even for a moment. She was never seen without a number of rings and necklaces - every single one was worn for a very specific purpose, and almost all of them were adorned with images of death. She had the fashion sense of someone who cared very much about coming across like she didn&amp;rsquo;t care at all.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bodach clicked his beak thoughtfully. His lithe, supple feet hopped onto the windowsill, and he eyed Lilith in a rather hungry sort of way.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Typical man,&amp;rdquo; she said. &amp;ldquo;Always expecting something in return.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She stood up and retrieved a bowl she had been using in her spell. One convenient thing about having a Raven familiar is that they like to eat a number of the more perishable spell ingredients, so it added a bit of synergy to the whole operation. Oneiromancy had an unpleasant need for small rodent parts, but luckily Bodach considered them a delicacy.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The other important task that Bodach performed for Lilith was as the proverbial whipping boy for her general opinions on the world. This was the main reason it was important for Bodach to be male.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;That&amp;rsquo;s right,&amp;rdquo; she said, stroking his black feathers. &amp;ldquo;Get fat and lazy and then leave.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bocachs through the years have had the important responsibility of bearing a great deal of avarice.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She stood and began tidying up the space, putting - or throwing - the spell ingredients away as necessary. Bodach watched her, trained to enjoy the sound of her voice. To him her presence implied affection and the possibility of further treats. He had imprinted on her some sense of avian social obligation. If he had known the real meaning of the words she said to him, he might have felt differently.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Perhaps that is why her raven relationships always worked. She understood the machinations of avian social structures, perhaps better than she understood the human counterparts. She slung insulting aphorisms at him because he was an impartial, friendly ear. Her words didn&amp;rsquo;t need to be understood. The important thing was that he never tried to argue with her. He always listened sweetly, intently, and then left her alone so he could find another piece of garbage to give her. In turn, she kept him warm, gave him whatever sense of purpose a raven requires, and filled him up with all the small rodent parts he could handle.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;We are very close, Bodey,&amp;rdquo; she was saying, organizing the bundles of dried herbs hanging from the ceiling around her. &amp;ldquo;It might even be a matter of months.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bodach clicked his beak.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I believe my sisters are coming around. They aren&amp;rsquo;t stupid men like you, so it has taken time to convince them.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bodach shook his tail.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Not long now, you fool. You useless little creature.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Bodach ruffled his beak under one of his wings. From the corner of his eye, he noticed some movement in a nearby tree outside. He spread his wings and gracefully lept from the windowsill. She let him go. He was her pet, but he didn&amp;rsquo;t live with her. She had realized many Bodachs ago that though it was quite difficult to get a raven to be a pet - it was impossible to get one to be a house pet.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;So very soon,&amp;rdquo; she said to herself now. &amp;ldquo;Then your kind will be no more.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She closed the window.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;This might seem like a skewed perspective of men. In fact, it is simply an example of things as they are. This should not be seen as an indictment of male kind in general. It is simply an indictment of awful people in general. Readers are encouraged to make their own conclusions about the fact that on the whole awful people in general seem to usually be men. It can be said that not all men are awful, but then it should also be said that all women will have, at some point, had to deal with a man who was.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div style=&quot;margin: 0 10vw; font-family: Arial&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;You write shitty articles nobody likes. That&amp;rsquo;s it. Nobody wil lcare when u die.I hope you enjoy you&amp;rsquo;re last moments alive on this earth. You did nothing worthwile with  your life. Good thing u dont have any kids because they would grow up to be feminist dykes and I am so sick of you feminiists.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Posted by Death to Diana&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In one of the city&amp;rsquo;s many coffee shops, a series of genuinely disturbing comments scrolled past a laptop screen. Diana Harbinger yawned as she read through them. It was nothing she hadn&amp;rsquo;t seen a hundred times before. She tipped the last few drops of coffee from her cup onto her tongue, and sighed. When she first started writing for PopCultural, Diana found something strangely exciting about the wall of hate spewed anonymously at her after each new article. After a few years of it, though, it was starting to feel like a cliche.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For many people, someone saying that they are going to be posting pictures of their mutilated corpse on the internet in the morning would be cause for alarm. For Diana, it was Thursday.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Diana&amp;rsquo;s editor regularly called her to make sure she was okay, which was a gesture she appreciated but didn&amp;rsquo;t need. He kept offering to ban some of the more vicious regulars, but he ultimately relented when she pointed out that the absurd drama was always good for ad sales. She found something exciting about the attention. She felt like she was doing something important by bringing these voices out into the light. She also really enjoyed making fun of them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Diana always loved giving people the finger, and the more they deserved it the more satisfaction she got.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A few blocks away, at a small, ancient diner, Evelyn Bailey was also yawning. She patiently awaited the end of her shift. A Thursday afternoon was not exactly a peak time, so the place was very quiet and almost deserted. It was a greasy spoon diner, though, so a few folks could be expected as a matter of course.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;At the counter sat an old man whose name everybody knew (in fact, everyone thought they knew his name, but they all thought it was something different and they were all wrong). He never spoke, but he was always there. Everyone knew what he ordered because it was the same thing he always ordered, and at this point serving him became as regular as taking out the garbage.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The chef - a large man with a name like Sal - was constantly occupied with the work of making it seem like the work of a greasy spoon cook was in fact the hardest job in the world. In some ways he wasn&amp;rsquo;t wrong, but in much more realistic ways the overworked and underpaid waitresses who had to serve his greasy abominations had it much worse.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He understood this, though, and so he did look out for his sisters in arms on the front lines of the quick service dining industry. They had the usual methods of recourse against those customers who made their lives difficult. Various innocuous-seeming code phrases on order tickets let the cook know what particular customers deserved. Known bad tippers had their signal, and handsy old men got theirs. Sal had little patience for disrespectful people in general, but he had even less patience for anyone who would make trouble for the people he had to work very long hours with. Revenge was a dish best served at the lukewarm temperature that everything served at a diner ends up being.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Around this time, Margaret Allen - fully awake this time - was trying to get her computer to cooperate. She was telling what she was supposed to tell it to get it to do what she wanted it to do. It just wasn&amp;rsquo;t doing it. Her firm had upgraded their design software earlier in the month, and a few of her favorite shortcuts had changed. She sighed to herself. She had only just gotten used to the new shortcuts after the last update. Things that work shouldn&amp;rsquo;t change.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She flicked the little rocking desk toy she kept near her keyboard. Unlike her stupid computer, it always worked. It was a pair of little wire figures balanced on either end of an armature, like two very skinny people sharing a seesaw. When flicked, the perfectly balanced figures rocked back and forth for a surprisingly long time. It was rather satisfying to watch them go, and counting the rocks helped her clear her mind. The record so far was two hundred forty eight.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The toy was positioned rather specifically, as was everything on her desk. It was a rather sacred space to her, as she made very clear to her coworkers. Once an intern at the firm needed some clear tape, and found Margaret&amp;rsquo;s dispenser (two inches left of her left monitor stand, just behind her stack of post-its, tape pointing to the left). She returned it almost immediately, placing it between Margaret&amp;rsquo;s post-its and her coffee mug. Several strongly-worded emails later, and it was determined that nobody in the office was to touch anything on her desk unless lives depended on it. She would have preferred dropping even that provision.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is one of the general rules of literature that an author never names a character something like &amp;ldquo;Dickweed.&amp;rdquo; It skews the character, and it forces readers to form opinions about them before they get to do anything. It is especially egregious in a script. An actor loses a great deal of freedom when they get a character simply referred to as &amp;ldquo;asshole.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is with full awareness of this rule that the next character will only be referred to as Dickweed Barista, because that tells you everything you need to know about him.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Diana&amp;rsquo;s hands were hovering over her keyboard to write a response to the comment she had just read. Before she could get very far, the music she was listening to was cut out. She was suddenly snapped back to the world of one of the city&amp;rsquo;s many coffee shops.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Dickweed Barista stood over Diana with a sickeningly friendly smile, one of her earbuds pinched between his finger and thumb. She stared at him, trying to come to grips with the situation, and just how violent she should be in response. The wails of Bikini Kill could still be heard coming from the little nub.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Need anything, honey?&amp;rdquo; He asked.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;The fuck?&amp;rdquo; She muttered.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Classic rock played innocuously as Evelyn looked up at the clock on the wall of the diner. The clock&amp;rsquo;s hands were barely visible through glass that had been frosted by decades of grime. Evelyn generally tried to avoid looking at the clock, because beneath all those layers of old grease, those hands somehow moved slower than normal clocks. Surrounding the clock was scores of junk, exactly the sort of junk that seems to just grow naturally on the walls of old diners. The ceiling was stained from cigarette smoke, despite the fact that cigarettes had been banned inside the place for over a decade. The whole place used to be mostly white, but at this point it was getting hard to tell. The white had given way over the decades to the greys, browns, and beiges that always follow in the wake of human society.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Evelyn spent more time in this grimy place than her own home, but it was her domain. She was the duchess of grease, and the diner was for all intents and purposes hers. Technically, her name wasn&amp;rsquo;t on the door (that said &amp;ldquo;Marcie&amp;rsquo;s&amp;rdquo;), her name wasn&amp;rsquo;t on anyone&amp;rsquo;s paycheck (except her own, of course), and she had little real authority. What she had was the authority of tenure, and the determination of someone who was far too tired to deal with any of bullshit. She knew how things worked, and made sure they continued to even though it wasn&amp;rsquo;t what she was paid to do.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She had collected the meager tips on her last table of the day when she heard a familiar voice. It was familiar in the way a chronic, stabbing pain is familiar. The trouble with being a longstanding waitress at a cheap restaurant (if you had to pick just one) was the occasional unbearable regular. This particular regular was called Eddie, and he had a thing for Evelyn. Evelyn had a thing for him, as well, but it was a very different thing with the words &amp;ldquo;pepper spray&amp;rdquo; printed on the side.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Hey, can I get some help over here?&amp;rdquo; Eddie asked. She rolled her eyes.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Heh, just kidding,&amp;rdquo; he continued. &amp;ldquo;You can take your time. I&#039;m enjoying the view.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Olympic athletes would be impressed by the tone and strength of Evelyn&amp;rsquo;s eye-rolling muscles.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Hey Margie,&amp;rdquo; said Margaret&amp;rsquo;s desk neighbor, making her lose count of the rocking toy on her desk.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Greg&lt;/em&gt;. He was a very short man, which always seemed like it confused him. He seemed to always gesturing at his stature, as if to say &amp;ldquo;surely this is all some sort of mistake.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s Margaret,&amp;rdquo; she said in a way that suggested she had said it a hundred times before.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Come take a look at these plans.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She scooted her meticulously adjusted office chair the few feet to his desk. Her desk toy continued rocking unmonitored.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m having trouble getting the clearance to work on this door,&amp;rdquo; he said, pointing at some meaningful lines on his screen. He often needed her to do his work for him.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, see, you don&amp;rsquo;t need a firewall there,&amp;rdquo; she said, pointing at some different, but equally meaningful lines.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;What&amp;rsquo;s the difference?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;A firewall has to be self-supporting,&amp;rdquo; she said, wondering if he even went to Architectural school. &amp;ldquo;A fire barrier only has to go up to the roof deck. You&amp;rsquo;ll have room for that other door there if you just use a barrier.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Hmm,&amp;rdquo; he said, his brow furrowing obnoxiously. &amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m not sure you know what you&amp;rsquo;re talking about.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Greg&lt;/em&gt;. The answer to the question, &amp;lsquo;what if Napoleon were an architect, and also an idiot?&amp;rsquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;One time, Margaret got to work to find that &lt;em&gt;Greg&lt;/em&gt; had moved everything on her desk an inch to the left. He did it as a prank. She didn&amp;rsquo;t have to notice him stifling laughter to realize what had happened, mainly because she noticed her desk was off from the elevator. She tried getting back at him by changing all of his chair adjustments while he was in the bathroom. He didn&amp;rsquo;t even notice. He just swung his stubby little legs that no longer reached the ground. It was infuriating&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, sorry, Dee,&amp;rdquo; said Dickweed Barista, handing Diana her earbud and returning to tidying the table next to her. &amp;ldquo;I was just wondering if you needed anything.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Die.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;What?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;My name. It&amp;rsquo;s not Dee. It&amp;rsquo;s Di.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh,&amp;rdquo; Dickweed responded with an unfortunate chuckle. &amp;ldquo;I was just going by what was written on your cup.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She looked down at her cup, marked &amp;lsquo;Diana,&amp;rsquo; and sighed. She had been forced to explain to people how to pronounce her name her entire life.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s &amp;lsquo;Die,&amp;rsquo; you know, like what we&amp;rsquo;re all going to do some day.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;What are you concentrating on so hard, anyway?&amp;rdquo; He responded, the not-so-subtle hints flying right over his head.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&#039;m working.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh yeah, you write for Pop Cultural, right?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She stared at him, knowing the large &amp;lsquo;Pop Cultural&amp;rsquo; sticker on her laptop was almost directly in his eye line.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Whatever gave you that idea?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Need anything else, Mike?&amp;rdquo; Evelyn asked the Man at the Bar as she refilled his coffee. She knew the answer, but it was still her job to ask and she took any chance she could to put off the same old conversation she had fake smiled her way through a hundred times before. She walked over to the booth Eddie had manspread himself into, and flipped to a new page in her order pad.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Alright, Eddie, what&#039;ll it be today?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;What, no specials?&amp;rdquo; He asked with the tone of someone who wasn&amp;rsquo;t talking about food.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Do you really want the specials?&amp;rdquo; She responded, with the tone of someone who wasn&amp;rsquo;t, either.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I just like hearing you talk.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Do you just want your usual?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Sure, you know me too well, Eve.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;It&#039;s Evelyn, and I kind of hope not.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Haha, nah.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&#039;m just finishing my shift, but I&#039;ll get this in for you.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, well, maybe I&#039;ll just get this to go and we can hang out.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Evelyn finished jotting down Eddie&amp;rsquo;s order, and suppressed a wince. What she needed was a big couch, a big beer, and a big distance between her and any thirsty boys.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Not tonight,&amp;rdquo; she said. &amp;ldquo;I, uh, have plans.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This was true. She always had standing plans specifically to be not hanging out with Eddie.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, sure,&amp;rdquo; Eddie replied, trying and failing to look nonchalant about it, &amp;ldquo;maybe next time. I want to make sure you get a tip, though. You know I tip well.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;He didn&amp;rsquo;t.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Just put it on your receipt when you pay, like usual,&amp;rdquo; she said.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Margaret&amp;rsquo;s boss, one of the partners of the firm, walked by &lt;em&gt;Greg&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/em&gt; desk looking over some papers. He was much taller than &lt;em&gt;Greg&lt;/em&gt;, a fact that often amused Margaret while her mind wandered during tedious team meetings.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Hey Margaret,&amp;rdquo; he said, &amp;ldquo;make sure you get that environmental impact report on the Northbrook project to me before you leave today.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;His sleeves were rolled up to his elbows. There was a different fabric print on the inside, as if they were designed to be rolled up to his elbows. One arm was rolled slightly higher than the other. All of this was deeply troubling to Margaret.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Sure, I was just about to send that to you.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;You know,&amp;rdquo; &lt;em&gt;Greg&lt;/em&gt; chimed in, leaning back in his chair. &amp;ldquo;I was thinking about that - there are definitely some simple ways to avoid some headaches on the plans.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Yup, I-&amp;rdquo; Margaret attempted.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;That&#039;s a good idea, Greg,&amp;rdquo; said their boss. &amp;ldquo;I think we&#039;ll want to make sure we get that into the report. Margie -&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Sir, it&amp;rsquo;s-&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Go ahead and send your findings to Greg so he can get that added in. Greg, you can get that to me next week some time. Thanks.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Greg&lt;/em&gt;. At least he didn&amp;rsquo;t have to stoop very low to reach the butts he kissed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Sure thing,&amp;rdquo; he said.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Great work,&amp;rdquo; said their boss with a smile. &amp;ldquo;Have a great weekend, guys.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Margaret sighed. She had been working on that report for two weeks. She had researched code requirements and survey reports on the site itself, and reconciled them with the needs of the client. That was, in her estimation, her job as an Architect, so it barely needed mentioning. However, considering &lt;em&gt;Greg&lt;/em&gt;probably didn&amp;rsquo;t even know what survey reports even were, she always felt the bar was pretty low (bonus height joke).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;You should smile more,&amp;rdquo; said Dickweed Barista.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Why?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I see you in here working all the time. You&#039;ll brighten my day.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That was enough for Diana. She slammed her laptop closed, and started collecting her things. A young woman out in public generally is going to get hit on, but she didn&amp;rsquo;t have to like it. Diana had done as much as she could, covering herself in tattoos and piercings, occasionally even shaving her head, but still the idiots would come along with their suggestions for how she could be prettier.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Listen, you&#039;re really not my type,&amp;rdquo; she said.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh, you&#039;re probably into, like, artistic guys?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;I&#039;m not into guys at all.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Oh awesome,&amp;rdquo; he said with a stupid grin. &amp;ldquo;You&#039;re a lesbian? That&#039;s hot.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Ugh, you just lost your talking privileges.&amp;rdquo; She said, visibly cringing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Hey, I&#039;m just trying to be friendly, honey.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;ldquo;Well, you&#039;re doing a real shitty job, sport.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;She stormed out of the coffee shop, leaving Dickweed holding his hands out in confusion.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Margaret gave her desk toy a flick and started working on an email. At least she still knew the shortcuts to Outlook.&lt;/p&gt;

